icy challenges, including campus (or workplace) diversity, individual responsibility, and the policy pitfalls of defining culture as something separate from social life. Bryson contends that cultural policy should abandon the "norms and values" definition of culture as individual beliefs and focus instead on the cultural implications of structure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teaching (Higher)zUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aMulticultural educationzUnited StatesvCase studies. 4aCultural Studies. 4aSociology -- Culture. 4aSociology -- Education and Society. 7aEDUCATION / Multicultural Education.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080475656340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804756563423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804756563/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles